Name: Emperor Constantius II
Description: 361 – Emperor Constantius II dies of a fever at Mopsuestia in Cilicia; on his deathbed he is baptised and declares his cousin Julian rightful successor.

Name: Rouen Riot
Description: 1090 – The Rouen Riot, an attempt by English king William Rufus to take possession of Rouen, the capital city of his brother Robert, duke of Normandy, fails.

Name: River Arno
Description: 1333 – The River Arno floods causing massive damage in Florence as recorded by the Florentine chronicler Giovanni Villani.

Name: Liège
Description: 1468 – Liège is sacked by Charles I of Burgundy's troops.

Name: Peace of Etaples
Description: 1492 – Peace of Etaples between Henry VII of England and Charles VIII of France.

Name: Christopher Columbus
Description: 1493 – Christopher Columbus first sights the island of Dominica in the Caribbean Sea.

Name: the first Act of Supremacy
Description: 1534 – English Parliament passes the first Act of Supremacy, making King Henry VIII head of the Anglican Church, supplanting the pope and the  Roman Catholic Church.

Name: Continental Army
Description: 1783 – The American Continental Army is disbanded.

Name: University of Vermont
Description: 1791 – The University of Vermont, the oldest university in Vermont, and fifth-oldest in New England, is chartered.

Name: feminist
Description: 1793 – French playwright, journalist and feminist Olympe de Gouges is guillotined.

Name: Napoleon
Description: 1812 – Napoleon's armies are defeated at the Battle of Vyazma.

Name: Bank of Montreal
Description: 1817 – The Bank of Montreal, Canada's oldest chartered bank, opens in Montreal.

Name: The Times of India
Description: 1838 – The Times of India, the world's largest circulated English language daily broadsheet newspaper is founded as The Bombay Times and Journal of Commerce.

Name: Dutch constitution
Description: 1848 – A greatly revised Dutch constitution, which transfers much authority from the king to his parliament and ministers, is proclaimed.

Name: Giuseppe Garibaldi
Description: 1867 – Giuseppe Garibaldi and his followers are defeated in the Battle of Mentana and fail to end the Pope's Temporal power in Rome (it would be achieved three years later).

Name: John Willis Menard
Description: 1868 – John Willis Menard (R-LA) was the first African American elected to the United States Congress.  Because of an electoral challenge, he was never seated.

Name: Mapuche uprising of 1881
Description: 1881 – The Mapuche uprising of 1881 begins in Chile.

Name: Fashoda
Description: 1898 – France withdraws its troops from Fashoda (now in Sudan), ending the Fashoda Incident.

Name: Panama
Description: 1903 – With the encouragement of the United States, Panama separates from Colombia.

Name: William Howard Taft
Description: 1908 – William Howard Taft is elected the 27th President of the United States.

Name: Chevrolet
Description: 1911 – Chevrolet officially enters the automobile market in competition with the Ford Model T.

Name: German Revolution of 1918–19
Description: 1918 – The German Revolution of 1918–19 begins when 40,000 sailors take over the port in Kiel.

Name: Russian Civil War
Description: 1920 – Russian Civil War: The Russian Army retreats to Crimea, after a successful offensive by the Red Army and Revolutionary Insurgent Army of Ukraine.

Name: Gwangju Student Independence Movement
Description: 1929 – The Gwangju Student Independence Movement occurred.

Name: Getúlio Vargas
Description: 1930 – Getúlio Vargas becomes Head of the Provisional Government in Brazil after a bloodless coup on October 24.

Name: Panagis Tsaldaris
Description: 1932 – Panagis Tsaldaris becomes the 142nd Prime Minister of Greece.

Name: George II of Greece
Description: 1935 – George II of Greece regains his throne through a popular, though possibly fixed, plebiscite.

Name: Franklin D. Roosevelt
Description: 1936 – Franklin D. Roosevelt is reelected as President of the United States.

Name: World War II
Description: 1942 – World War II: The Koli Point action begins during the Guadalcanal campaign and ends on November 12.

Name: devastate Wilhelmshaven
Description: 1943 – World War II: Five hundred aircraft of the U.S. 8th Air Force devastate Wilhelmshaven harbor in Germany.

Name: Slovak National Uprising
Description: 1944 – World War II: Two supreme commanders of the Slovak National Uprising, Generals Ján Golian and Rudolf Viest, are captured, tortured and later executed by German forces.

Name: Constitution of Japan
Description: 1946 – The Constitution of Japan is adopted through Emperor's assent.

Name: Battle of Dengbu Island
Description: 1949 – Chinese Civil War: The Battle of Dengbu Island occurs.

Name: Air India Flight 245
Description: 1950 – Air India Flight 245 crashes into Mont Blanc while on approach to Geneva Airport, killing all 48 people on board.

Name: Suez Crisis
Description: 1956 – Suez Crisis: The Khan Yunis killings by the Israel Defense Forces in Egyptian-controlled Gaza result in the deaths of 275 Palestinians.

Name: Hungarian Revolution
Description: 1956   – Hungarian Revolution: A new Hungarian government is formed, in which many members of banned non-Communist parties participate.  János Kádár and Ferenc Münnich form a counter-government in Moscow as Soviet troops prepare for the final assault.

Name: Sputnik program
Description: 1957 – Sputnik program: The Soviet Union launches Sputnik 2. On board is the first animal to enter orbit, a dog named Laika.

Name: Great Swamp National Wildlife Refuge
Description: 1960 – The land that would become the Great Swamp National Wildlife Refuge is established by an Act of Congress after a year-long legal battle that pitted local residents against Port Authority of New York and New Jersey officials wishing to turn the Great Swamp into a major regional airport for jet aircraft.

Name: U Thant
Description: 1961 – U Thant is unanimously appointed as the 3rd Secretary-General of the United Nations, becoming the first non-European individual to occupy the post.

Name: Lyndon B. Johnson
Description: 1964 – Lyndon B. Johnson is elected to a full term as U.S. president, winning 61% of the vote and 44 states, while Washington D.C. residents are able to vote in a presidential election for the first time, casting the majority of their votes for Lyndon Johnson.

Name: Vietnam War
Description: 1967 – Vietnam War: The Battle of Dak To begins.

Name: Richard M. Nixon
Description: 1969 – Vietnam War: U.S. President Richard M. Nixon addresses the nation on television and radio, asking the "silent majority" to join him in solidarity on the Vietnam War effort and to support his policies.

Name: Mariner program
Description: 1973 – Mariner program: NASA launches the Mariner 10 toward Mercury. On March 29, 1974, it becomes the first space probe to reach that planet.

Name: killed
Description: 1975 – Four Bangladeshi politicians are killed in the Dhaka Central Jail.

Name: Dominica
Description: 1978 – Dominica gains its independence from the United Kingdom.

Name: Greensboro massacre
Description: 1979 – Greensboro massacre: Five members of the Communist Workers Party are shot dead and seven are wounded by a group of Klansmen and neo-Nazis during a "Death to the Klan" rally in Greensboro, North Carolina, United States.

Name: Latin Carga
Description: 1980 – A Latin Carga Convair CV-880 crashes at Simón Bolívar International Airport in Venezuela, killing four.

Name: Salang Tunnel fire
Description: 1982 – The Salang Tunnel fire in Afghanistan kills 150–2000 people.

Name: Iran–Contra affair
Description: 1986 – Iran–Contra affair: The Lebanese magazine Ash-Shiraa reports that the United States has been secretly selling weapons to Iran in order to secure the release of seven American hostages held by pro-Iranian groups in Lebanon.

Name: Compact of Free Association
Description: 1986   – The Compact of Free Association becomes law, granting the Federated States of Micronesia and the Marshall Islands independence from the United States.

Name: Sri Lankan
Description: 1988 – Sri Lankan Tamil mercenaries attempt to overthrow the Maldivian government. At President Maumoon Abdul Gayoom's request, the Indian military suppresses the rebellion within 24 hours.

Name: Arkansas
Description: 1992 – Democratic Arkansas Governor Bill Clinton defeats Republican President George H. W. Bush and Independent candidate Ross Perot in the 1992 United States presidential election.

Name: Space Shuttle program
Description: 1994 – Space Shuttle program: Atlantis launches on STS-66.

Name: Abdullah Çatlı
Description: 1996 – Abdullah Çatlı, the leader of the Turkish ultranationalist organization Grey Wolves, dies in the Susurluk car crash, leading to the resignation of Interior Minister Mehmet Ağar (a leader of the True Path Party).

Name: economic sanctions
Description: 1997 – The United States imposes economic sanctions against Sudan in response to its human rights abuses of its own citizens and its material and political assistance to Islamic extremist groups across the Middle East and East Africa.

Name: One World Trade Center
Description: 2014 – One World Trade Center officially opens in New York City, replacing the Twin Towers after they were destroyed during the September 11 attacks.

Name: 2020 United States presidential election
Description: 2020 – The 2020 United States presidential election takes place between Democratic Joe Biden and Republican incumbent President Donald Trump. On November 7, Biden was declared the winner.
